Netflix for bondsThere is a modern quantitative approach to stock trading t=
hat views every stock as a=C2=A0linear combination of exposures to some set=
 of factors, so that each stock (or ETF) is equivalent to some combination =
of other stocks (or ETFs). One Tesla share equals half an Apple share plus =
two Facebooks, nine GameStops, six AMCs and a Ford, or whatever, that sort =
of thing, but much more rigorous and less intuitive. It=E2=80=99s not like =
you sit down and think about what the factors are and then try to put toget=
her a basket of those factors; it=E2=80=99s just like you run a big regress=
ion on a lot of historical data points and say =E2=80=9Cthis stock is equal=
 to this combination of these 438 stocks.=E2=80=9D And then you can do high=
-frequency market making in one stock and hedge it in other stocks, keeping=
 your book balanced on some aggregate set of factors rather than on any ind=
ividual stock. And you just put it in the hands of a computer and go off an=
d do something else, satisfied that the stock market is very liquid and the=
re are lots of close substitutes for each stock and the computer can figure=
 it out.In=C2=A0bonds, you might in some sense expect this to be easier; th=
e bonds of two companies with correlated stocks should be even more correla=
ted, and of course two bonds of the same company should be very correlated =
indeed. But in fact bonds are less liquid and more weird and it=E2=80=99s a=
lways possible that the model would say =E2=80=9CBond X is equal to 0.54 Bo=
nd A and 0.31 Bond B and 0.15 Bond C=E2=80=9D and you=E2=80=99d be like =E2=
=80=9Cahh but Bond C is all owned by a single insurance company that won=E2=
=80=99t sell it to me unless I answer three riddles so that=E2=80=99s out.=
=E2=80=9D=C2=A0 Or: =E2=80=9CBut Bond B has a weird provision in the back o=
f the document that says I don=E2=80=99t get paid back if a comet appears w=
hen the moon is full.=E2=80=9D You can=E2=80=99t just leave a=C2=A0quantita=
tive strategy in the hands of a computer and figure the computer can handle=
 it.Instead what you want is for the computer to tell you about the correla=
tions, so you can make informed investing decisions, but leave it to you to=
=C2=A0act=C2=A0on those correlations, so you can make use of your occult kn=
owledge of bonds. Here=E2=80=99s a fun story about how =E2=80=9C Wall Stree=
t=E2=80=99s Math Whizzes Are Racing to Wire Up the Bond Market.=E2=80=9D As=
 usual there=E2=80=99s stuff about how =E2=80=9Celectronic venues like Mark=
etAxess and Tradeweb accounted for 37% of investment-grade and 26% of high-=
yield trading in May, 8 percentage points higher than the year before,=E2=
=80=9D but there=E2=80=99s also this:Over at banks=E2=80=99 trading desks, =
Asita Anche at Barclays Plc has seen a jump in algo usage, especially to ex=
ecute small trades. But she stresses that humans are still essential in fix=
ed income since liquidity is more fragmented than in equities and it=E2=80=
=99s harder to manage risk.=E2=80=9CThe future is not algos taking flows aw=
ay from humans,=E2=80=9D said the head of systematic market making and data=
 science. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s humans enhanced by algos and automation.=E2=
=80=9DWith that in mind, Anche is building algos and data analytics for voi=
ce traders, and even a recommendation engine akin to Netflix=E2=80=99s that=
 finds similar securities to what a client wants to trade.=E2=80=9CIf you l=
ike Bond X, you=E2=80=99ll love Bonds A, B and C,=E2=80=9D the computer tel=
ls you, and then you get to have the=C2=A0satisfaction of telling the compu=
ter =E2=80=9CBond A, great choice, thanks, but you don=E2=80=99t understand=
 anything about Bond C at all.=E2=80=9DBinanceBinance is a cryptocurrency e=
xchange, headquartered nowhere, that offers highly levered cryptocurrency f=
utures to retail traders.=C2=A0The way it apparently works is that you put =
in $1,000, and if the price of Bitcoin goes up by 1% you make $1,000, and i=
f the price of Bitcoin goes up by 20% you make $20,000 and think you=E2=80=
=99re the best trader in the world, but if the price of Bitcoin goes down b=
y 1% you lose all your money.[1] The price of Bitcoin is very volatile. Bas=
ically the outcome you should expect from this game is that (1) a lot of pe=
ople will start trading and have large quick paper gains, (2) they will thi=
nk they are the best traders in the world, (3) they will quit their jobs to=
 trade leveraged crypto futures full-time, (4) eventually they will almost =
certainly lose all of their money, and (5) they will get mad and complain t=
o journalists about it.The specific mechanism in this Wall Street Journal s=
tory=C2=A0is that, as the price of Bitcoin was going down, Binance=E2=80=99=
s website and app froze and all those great traders couldn=E2=80=99t make s=
mart defensive moves to preserve their massive wealth, but whatever man:Ano=
ther member of the group is Kate Marie, a 59-year-old healthcare technology=
 consultant in Sydney, who dipped into the world of crypto futures in early=
 2020 after her business was dissolved over a dispute.After reading =E2=80=
=9CTrend Trading for Dummies,=E2=80=9D and watching YouTube tutorials, Ms. =
Marie said she began trading with $10,000. With a bull market on her side, =
she had built $450,000 by April. She felt reassured using Binance because o=
f its market dominant position and global reach.=E2=80=9CThat=E2=80=99s the=
 thing about crypto trading: It gives the poor the same chances that the ri=
ch have to make money,=E2=80=9D she said.But then May 19 came. Ms. Marie sa=
id as prices of several currencies she had in her portfolio sank, she was u=
nable to change her positions because she couldn=E2=80=99t access her accou=
nt via the Binance application.Ms. Marie said she had experienced localized=
 crashes at Binance before, but this one was widespread and lasted longer, =
enough for her to be almost entirely liquidated, losing some $170,000 she h=
ad, based on the time of the liquidation.=E2=80=9CI feel cheated,=E2=80=9D =
Ms. Marie said.You were definitely cheated, but also you were definitely go=
ing to lose all your money one way or another. Here=E2=80=99s another:=C2=
=A0Toronto resident Fawaz Ahmed, 33, had been trading full time since early=
 2020. He said he amassed coins trading futures on Binance and hoped to mak=
e enough to let his parents retire and help his siblings through college. H=
e lives at home with his parents.On May 19, he said he had 1,250 ether coin=
s, at the time worth around $3 million. When he saw ether begin to slide, h=
e clicked the app to exit his positions, take losses and move on. But the B=
inance app on his phone was frozen and nothing would click, he said. He kep=
t trying for about an hour.Then he received a message saying he had been li=
quidated as his losses surpassed the collateral.Yeah. Ether was down 26% th=
at day. If you have a 5x or 20x or 125x levered position on something that =
goes down 26% in a day,=C2=A0maybe=C2=A0you won=E2=80=99t lose all your mon=
ey if the app doesn=E2=80=99t crash, but, you know,=C2=A0probably=C2=A0you=
=E2=80=99re gonna lose all your money.These people are apparently banding t=
ogether to ask=C2=A0Binance for their money back, but they are stymied by t=
he facts that Binance doesn=E2=80=99t have their money, doesn=E2=80=99t car=
e, and in some important legal and practical senses doesn=E2=80=99t exist:B=
inance traders around the world have been trying to get their money back. B=
ut unlike a more traditional investment platform, Binance is largely unregu=
lated and has no headquarters, making it difficult, the traders say, to fig=
ure out whom to petition.Mr. Singhal has joined a group of about 700 trader=
s who are working with a lawyer in France to recoup their losses. In Italy,=
 another group is petitioning Binance over the same issue. Lawyers represen=
ting the Italy group sent a letter to 11 Binance addresses they could find =
in Europe, and an email to the help desk.Ooh a petition.=C2=A0There=E2=80=
=99s gonna be another story like this in a month. The supply of people who =
quit their jobs to trade leveraged crypto futures and then are sad when the=
y lose all their money does not seem to be affected by all the stories abou=
t people who quit their jobs to trade leveraged crypto futures and then wer=
e sad when they lost all their money. Somebody is reading this right now an=
d thinking =E2=80=9Chuh I should quit my job to trade leveraged crypto futu=
res.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CThat=E2=80=99s the thing about crypto trading: It gi=
ves the poor the same chances that the rich have to make money,=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0a woman who lost all her money on crypto trading says=C2=A0now. Yes! Tha=
t is the thing about crypto trading! That=E2=80=99s the one thing! Crypto t=
rading is a way for normal people=C2=A0to get rich easily and with no probl=
ems!=C2=A0That=E2=80=99s the lesson to take away from this story, absolutel=
y!=E2=80=9CCrypto Exchanges Have a Plan to Beat Binance: Play by the Rules=
=E2=80=9DThat=E2=80=99s the headline of  this story=C2=A0about U.S.-regulat=
ed crypto exchanges (Coinbase Global Inc., Gemini Trust Co., etc.) whose co=
mpetitive advantage against Binance is that they are more or less legal:The=
 idea is that if an exchange appeases U.S. authorities, it can probably ope=
rate just about anywhere and more easily lure institutional investors, such=
 as hedge funds, family offices, and pension funds. But with each step a pl=
atform takes, it goes further toward emulating the staid financial world, w=
here internal controls, industry groups, and regulators hold sway. =E2=80=
=9CThe Catch-22 is that the crypto system was set up to avoid big banks,=E2=
=80=9D says John Griffin, a professor of finance at the University of Texas=
 at Austin=E2=80=99s McCombs School of Business. But =E2=80=9Crather than h=
aving this autonomous universe free of government regulation, we have crypt=
o exchanges playing the role that traditional exchanges and governments pla=
y in traditional markets.=E2=80=9DI mean, fine. If you are looking to attra=
ct large institutional investors, =E2=80=9Cwe are a regulated crypto exchan=
ge, your limited partners won=E2=80=99t freak out if you use us, and we won=
=E2=80=99t steal all your money=E2=80=9D is actually a good pitch. If you a=
re looking to attract retail gamblers I suspect it is worse than =E2=80=9Cw=
e exist nowhere and are subject to no rules, but we=E2=80=99ll give you 125=
x leverage.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=E2=80=9CInvestors Trusted Teenagers to Manage Cr=
ypto Investments. Now They Want Answers.=E2=80=9DThe answer is that you tru=
sted teenagers to manage your crypto investments.=C2=A0Things happenCredit =
Suisse Adds Risk Role to Prevent Another Archegos. Is Palantir Buying Reven=
ue?=C2=A0The Meme Stock Fantasy Is Becoming a Reality for GameStop and AMC.=
 Hedge Fund Managers Who Are Mothers Saw Weaker Performance During Pandemic=
-Related School Closures. Inside the secret club that helps prepare young C=
EOs to take over the world. The World=E2=80=99s Billionaire Factory Shudder=
s as  China Cracks Down.=C2=A0Business Trips Are Coming Back Faster Than Ex=
pected in the U.S.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CThe fish are between 1-3 inches long, so t=
hey flutter down slowly to the water.=E2=80=9DIf you'd like to get=C2=A0Mon=
ey=C2=A0Stuff=C2=A0in handy email form, right in your inbox, please=C2=A0su=
bscribe at this link. Or you can subscribe to Money Stuff and other great B=
loomberg newsletters here. Thanks![1] I=E2=80=99m assuming 100-to-1 leverag=
e for simplicity. In fact that=E2=80=99s conservative! The Wall Street Jour=
nal says: =E2=80=9CTo make returns more attractive, traders on its main web=
site can make oversize bets with little money. Investors can get leverage o=
f 125 to 1 for some futures contracts, meaning they can deposit just 80 cen=
ts to amass the equivalent of $100 of bitcoin or another currency.=E2=80=9D=
 Binance itself says: =E2=80=9CTraders are able to select any leverage from=
 125x to 1x and larger positions will adjust to lower leverage allowed. At =
125x leverage, a 100 USDT collateral deposit on Binance Futures will allow =
users to hold 12,500 USDT in BTC.=E2=80=9D
